In this posting:
[1] Arizona
[2] Pomegranate seeds ex Turkey

******
[1] Arizona
Date: Thu 6 Jun 2013
Source: KTAR, The Voice of Arizona [edited]
http://ktar.com/22/1639768/Number-of-berrycaused-hepatitis-A-cases-doubles


The number of hepatitis A cases linked to frozen berries sold at a warehouse grocery store has doubled in less than a week. "The 61 cases are spread over 7 states," said Dr Rebecca Sunenshine with Maricopa County Public Health. "We have 9 cases total in Arizona, 7 of which are in Maricopa County."

Costco pulled Townsend Farms Organic Antioxidant Blend frozen berry mix from shelves after the news of the outbreak. Sunenshine said anyone who consumed the berries within 14 days can get a vaccine to prevent illness, if it's been longer the vaccine will be ineffective. "For those folks, you need to watch for symptoms of hepatitis A and if there are any concerns, see your healthcare provider," she said.

Hepatitis A is a viral disease that affects the liver. It develops 2 to 6 weeks after exposure. Disease symptoms include: fever, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting abdominal pain, and yellowing of the skin. Maricopa County Public Health is offering free hepatitis A vaccines.

[Byline: Sandra Haros]

